[El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) stands as the westernmost [county](/County_(United_States)) within the sprawling [U.S. state](/U.S._state) of [Texas](/Texas). One might say it's on the edge of everything, geographically and culturally, a place where the American West truly begins to blend into something else entirely. As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), this unique corner of the state recorded a population of 865,657, solidifying its position as the ninth-most populous [county in Texas](/List_of_counties_in_Texas). Its administrative core, the [county seat](/County_seat), is the city of [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas), a metropolis that itself claims the title of the [sixth-most populous city in Texas](/List_of_cities_in_Texas_by_population) and the [22nd-most populous city in the United States](/List_of_United_States_cities_by_population). The county's origins trace back to its creation in 1850, though it wasn't formally organized until 1871, a timeline that suggests a certain casual approach to bureaucracy, even then.

The name "El Paso" itself is derived from "El Paso del Norte," a [Spanish](/Spanish_language) phrase meaning "the Route of the North." This nomenclature is a direct reference to the natural pass carved by the mighty [Rio Grande](/Rio_Grande) as it cuts through the mountains that flank the river on either side. It's a geographical feature that has dictated migration, trade, and conflict for centuries, making it far more than just a scenic view. The county's location, directly northeast of the [Mexico–United States border](/Mexico%E2%80%93United_States_border), means it functions as a crucial, if perpetually complex, gateway between two nations.

[El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) forms the heart of the [El Paso metropolitan area](/El_Paso_metropolitan_area), a vibrant urban expanse that spills across international lines. What truly sets it apart, beyond its borderland identity, is its temporal anomaly within [Texas](/Texas). Along with [Hudspeth County](/Hudspeth_County,_Texas), [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) is one of only two counties in [Texas](/Texas) that operate entirely within the [Mountain Time Zone](/Mountain_Time_Zone). Every other county in the state, with the minor exception of northwestern [Culberson County](/Culberson_County,_Texas), adheres to [Central Time](/Central_Time_Zone_(North_America)). This distinction ensures that when the rest of [Texas](/Texas) is already well into its day, [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas) is still contemplating its first cup of coffee, a subtle but persistent reminder of its unique detachment. Furthermore, [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) is one of the nine counties that collectively define the [Trans-Pecos](/Trans-Pecos) region, a distinct and often rugged landscape of [West Texas](/West_Texas) known for its arid beauty and stark, unyielding terrain.

## Geography

[El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) is strategically positioned right on the [US-Mexico border](/Mexico%E2%80%93United_States_border), a geographical fact that defines much of its character and challenges. According to the ever-diligent [U.S. Census Bureau](/U.S._Census_Bureau), the county encompasses a total area of 1,015 square miles (2,630&#160;km<sup>2</sup>). Of this considerable expanse, a mere 2.3 square miles (6.0&#160;km<sup>2</sup>), or 0.2%, is covered by water, a testament to the arid, desert environment that dominates the region. Most of the land is, predictably, dry and rugged, shaped by ancient geological forces and the ceaseless sun.

### Adjacent counties and municipalities

The county's borders aren't just lines on a map; they represent vital intersections with neighboring jurisdictions, both within the [United States](/United_States) and across the international boundary.

*   [**Doña Ana County, New Mexico**](/Do%C3%B1a_Ana_County,_New_Mexico) – Situated to the northwest, this New Mexican neighbor shares a significant portion of its cultural and economic life with [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas), forming part of a larger bi-state community that often disregards state lines in its daily rhythm.
*   [**Otero County, New Mexico**](/Otero_County,_New_Mexico) – To the northeast lies [Otero County](/Otero_County,_New_Mexico), extending the New Mexican influence further into the regional tapestry.
*   [**Hudspeth County, Texas**](/Hudspeth_County,_Texas) – Directly to the east, [Hudspeth County](/Hudspeth_County,_Texas) mirrors [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas)'s [Mountain Time Zone](/Mountain_Time_Zone) distinction, a rare shared trait in [Texas](/Texas). It's a vast, sparsely populated area that serves as a buffer to the rest of [Texas](/Texas).
*   [**Guadalupe, Chihuahua, Mexico**](/Guadalupe_(municipality_of_Chihuahua)) – To the south, across the [Rio Grande](/Rio_Grande), lies the [municipality of Guadalupe](/Guadalupe_(municipality_of_Chihuahua)) in the Mexican state of [Chihuahua](/Chihuahua_(state)), a direct link to the cultural and economic flows of [Mexico](/Mexico).
*   [**Juárez, Chihuahua, Mexico**](/Ju%C3%A1rez_(municipality_of_Chihuahua)) – Also to the south, and perhaps the most significant adjacent entity, is [Ciudad Juárez](/Ju%C3%A1rez_(municipality_of_Chihuahua)). This vibrant Mexican city forms a single, massive urban conurbation with [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas), their fates inextricably linked, creating one of the largest binational metropolitan areas in the world.
*   [**Práxedis G. Guerrero, Chihuahua, Mexico**](/Pr%C3%A1xedis_G._Guerrero_(municipality)) – To the southeast, this smaller Mexican municipality further emphasizes the deep connections and daily crossings that define life on this border.

### National protected area

Within its bounds, [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) hosts sites of national significance, marking its historical and natural importance.
*   [**Chamizal National Memorial**](/Chamizal_National_Memorial) – This memorial commemorates the peaceful resolution of a century-long border dispute between the [United States](/United_States) and [Mexico](/Mexico) over the shifting course of the [Rio Grande](/Rio_Grande). It serves as a symbol of diplomacy and cultural exchange, a testament to what can be achieved when nations decide to talk rather than fight.
*   [**El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro National Historic Trail**](/El_Camino_Real_de_Tierra_Adentro_National_Historic_Trail) (part) – A segment of this ancient trade route, stretching from [Mexico City](/Mexico_City) to [San Juan Pueblo, New Mexico](/Ohkay_Owingeh), passes through [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas). It marks the historical path of Spanish colonization, trade, and cultural diffusion, a silent reminder of the deep historical roots that crisscross this landscape.

### Major highways

The county's infrastructure is dominated by a network of highways, serving as vital arteries for trade, commuters, and the occasional lost tourist. These roads are the lifeblood of the region, connecting its diverse communities and linking it to the wider national grid.
*   [I-10](/Interstate_10_in_Texas): The primary east-west interstate, a continuous ribbon of asphalt stretching across the southern [United States](/United_States), cutting directly through [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas).
*   [I-110](/Interstate_110_(Texas)): A short spur route connecting [I-10](/Interstate_10_in_Texas) to the [Bridge of the Americas](/Bridge_of_the_Americas) and [Mexico](/Mexico).
*   [US 54](/U.S._Route_54_in_Texas): A major north-south route, providing direct access to [New Mexico](/New_Mexico).
*   [Bus. US 54](/U.S._Route_54_Business_(El_Paso,_Texas)): The business loop for [US 54](/U.S._Route_54_in_Texas) within [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas).
*   [US 62](/U.S._Route_62_in_Texas): An east-west route, often co-signed with [US 180](/U.S._Route_180_in_Texas).
*   [US 180](/U.S._Route_180_in_Texas): Another significant east-west highway.
*   [SH 20](/Texas_State_Highway_20): A state highway running through the county.
*   [SH 178](/Texas_State_Highway_178): A state highway serving local traffic.
*   [Loop 375](/Texas_State_Highway_Loop_375): A critical beltway that encircles the city of [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas), easing traffic flow and connecting various parts of the metropolitan area.
*   [Loop 478](/Texas_State_Highway_Loop_478): Another loop within the county.
*   [Spur 6](/Texas_State_Highway_Spur_6): A state highway spur.
*   [Spur 16](/Texas_State_Highway_Spur_16): Another state highway spur.
*   [Spur 320](/Texas_State_Highway_Spur_320): A state highway spur.
*   [Spur 601](/Texas_State_Highway_Spur_601): This spur serves [Fort Bliss](/Fort_Bliss), providing essential access to the military installation.

