The racial and ethnic composition of [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) reveals a profound and continuous demographic transformation, particularly in its dominant [Hispanic/Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) majority. As of the [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_Census), the county's population stood at 800,647. The overwhelming majority, 82.1%, identified as [White](/White_Americans), predominantly of [Hispanic](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) descent, a categorization that speaks volumes about the region's historical and cultural ties to [Mexico](/Mexico). Other racial categories made up smaller but significant portions: 10.5% identified as other races, 3.1% as [African American](/African_Americans) or [Black](/Black_people), 2.5% as [of two or more races](/Multiracial_American), 1.0% as [Asian](/Asian_Americans), 0.8% as [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States), and a mere 0.1% as [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islands_Americans). The overarching demographic reality, however, was that 82.2% of the total population identified as [Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans), regardless of their specific racial self-identification. This figure underscores the deep-rooted Hispanic heritage that forms the very fabric of [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas).

A look back at the [census](/Census) of 2000 provides further context to these trends. At that time, the county was home to 679,622 people distributed across 210,022 households, with 166,127 of those being family units. The [population density](/Population_density) then was approximately 671 people per square mile (259 people/km<sup>2</sup>), a figure that speaks to the concentrated urban core surrounded by vast, less populated areas. Housing was relatively abundant, with 224,447 housing units recorded, averaging 222 per square mile (86/km<sup>2</sup>). The city's [Latino](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) population was already substantial, accounting for 78.23% of any race. The racial composition in 2000 was 73.95% [White](/White_Americans), 17.91% from other races, 3.06% [African American](/African_Americans) or [Black](/Black_people), 0.82% [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States), 0.98% [Asian](/Asian_Americans), 0.10% [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islands_Americans), and 3.19% from [two or more races](/Multiracial_American).

Delving deeper into the social fabric of 2000, 44.90% of the 210,022 households included children under the age of 18, indicating a youthful and family-oriented population. [Married couples](/Marriage) living together constituted 56.70% of households, while 18.00% were female householders with no husband present, reflecting diverse family structures. Non-family households made up 20.90% of the total, with 17.80% of all households consisting of individuals living alone. A notable 6.70% of these single-person households were occupied by someone 65 years of age or older, hinting at a growing elderly population. The average household size was a robust 3.18, and the average family size even larger at 3.63, pointing to close-knit, often extended, family units.

The age distribution in 2000 showed a significant concentration of youth, with 32.00% of the population under 18. Young adults aged 18 to 24 comprised 10.60%, while the largest segment, 29.30%, fell into the 25 to 44 age bracket, representing the core workforce. Those aged 45 to 64 made up 18.40%, and individuals 65 years of age or older accounted for 9.70%. The median age was a relatively young 30 years. Gender distribution showed a slight imbalance, with 93.20 males for every 100 females across the entire population, and 88.70 males for every 100 females aged 18 and over.

Economically, the median income for a household in [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) in 2000 was $31,051, with families earning a median of $33,410. Male workers typically earned $26,882, while females earned $20,722, highlighting a persistent wage gap. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the county was $13,421, a figure that suggests a community with significant economic challenges. Indeed, about 20.50% of families and a striking 23.80% of the overall population were living below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line). This included a disproportionate 31.50% of those under 18 and 18.50% of those aged 65 or over, indicating that both the youngest and oldest segments of the population were particularly vulnerable to economic hardship. These statistics paint a picture of a dynamic, rapidly growing community grappling with significant economic disparities, a common narrative in many border regions.

## Government and politics

[El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas)'s political landscape is, like many things here, distinct and often contrary to statewide trends. Historically, it has been a staunchly [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) stronghold, a blue island in a sea of red [Texas](/Texas). While the rest of the state often leans conservative, [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas) consistently throws its weight behind [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) candidates. Most of [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas) falls within the [16th Congressional District](/Texas%27s_16th_congressional_district) in the [U.S. House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives), currently represented by [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Veronica Escobar](/Veronica_Escobar). A smaller, eastern sliver of the county, however, finds itself in the [23rd Congressional District](/Texas%27s_23rd_congressional_district), which, since 2021, has been represented by [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) [Tony Gonzales](/Tony_Gonzales), a geographical and political split that perhaps reflects the divergent interests within the county's broader boundaries.

The [2008 presidential election](/2008_United_States_presidential_election_in_Texas) served as a prime example of [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas)'s [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) loyalty. [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) secured a resounding 66% of the vote, accumulating 121,589 votes, even as he lost the entire state of [Texas](/Texas) by a significant margin of approximately 946,000 votes. [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) [John McCain](/John_McCain), despite being the statewide favorite, managed only 33% of the vote in [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas), totaling 61,598 votes, with other candidates barely registering 1%. This pattern was consistent with the [2004 election](/2004_United_States_presidential_election_in_Texas) where [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [John F. Kerry](/John_F._Kerry) also carried [El Paso County](/El_Paso_County,_Texas), though by a narrower margin than [Obama](/Barack_Obama). [Kerry](/John_F._Kerry) garnered 56% of the vote, while [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) and former [Texas](/Texas) Governor [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush) received 43%, with 73,261 votes.

However, even historically entrenched political leanings are not immune to the shifting sands of public opinion. The [2024 election](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_Texas) presented a notable, if somewhat unsettling, deviation from this long-standing trend. [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) achieved the highest vote share for a [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) in the county since 2004, capturing 41.8% of the vote. This represented a substantial 20-point shift in margin towards the right compared to his 2020 performance. This significant movement was largely attributed to increased support for [Trump](/Donald_Trump) among [Latinos](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) in [Texas](/Texas), a demographic he notably won statewide with 54%. It's a stark reminder that even the most predictable political landscapes can surprise you, proving that loyalty is often conditional, especially when perceived interests shift.

