## National Historic Landmark

The [Rio Vista Bracero Reception Center](/Rio_Vista_Bracero_Reception_Center) achieved the esteemed designation of a [National Historic Landmark](/National_Historic_Landmark) on December 11, 2023, a decision officially made by the [U.S. Secretary of the Interior](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Interior), [Deb Haaland](/Deb_Haaland). This recognition is a profound acknowledgment of the site's critical role in American history, specifically related to the [Bracero Program](/Bracero_Program). The designation encompasses the historic Rio Vista Farm buildings and the surrounding agricultural fields in [Socorro, TX](/Socorro,_Texas), which together formed a key processing center for Mexican guest workers entering the [United States](/United_States) between 1951 and 1964. The [Bracero Program](/Bracero_Program) brought millions of Mexican laborers to work in U.S. agriculture, and sites like Rio Vista were the initial points of entry, medical examination, and contract signing. This landmark status ensures the preservation of a place that stands as a tangible reminder of the complex and often challenging history of labor, migration, and international relations between [Mexico](/Mexico) and the [United States](/United_States). It's a testament to the lives and struggles of countless individuals who passed through its gates, shaping the agricultural landscape and demographic future of the nation.

